    summary:
      "OpenAI has officially released GPT-5, boasting unprecedented reasoning abilities and multimodal capabilities that outperform every existing benchmark by a wide margin.",
    types: ["main", "sidebar"],
    body: `<p>OpenAI has officially launched GPT-5, its most powerful language model to date, marking what many experts are calling a defining moment in the history of artificial intelligence. The model was unveiled at a live event in San Francisco, where CEO Sam Altman described it as a system that can reason, plan, and execute complex multi-step tasks with a level of reliability that previous generations could not approach.</p>
 
  <h2>Unprecedented Performance Across Every Benchmark</h2>
    <p>According to OpenAI's internal evaluations, GPT-5 surpasses all existing models on over 40 standard AI benchmarks, including MMLU, HumanEval, and the newly introduced ARC-AGI-2 reasoning suite. Perhaps most strikingly, the model achieves near-human performance on the bar exam, medical licensing tests, and graduate-level mathematics — tasks that even GPT-4 struggled with consistently.</p>
 <p>Independent researchers who were given early access described the model as a qualitative leap forward. <strong>"It doesn't just answer questions — it thinks through them,"</strong> said Dr. Emily Chen, a cognitive scientist at Stanford University who participated in the evaluation program. "There are moments where the output is genuinely indistinguishable from that of a domain expert."</p>
 
<h2>New Multimodal and Agentic Capabilities</h2>
<p>GPT-5 natively processes text, images, audio, video, and code within a single unified architecture. Users can, for example, upload a video of a broken mechanical component and receive a step-by-step repair guide, or describe a business problem verbally and get back a working spreadsheet model. OpenAI has also introduced what it calls "agentic mode," which allows the model to autonomously browse the web, run code, manage files, and complete long-horizon tasks without human input at each step.</p>
<p>The model is available immediately to ChatGPT Pro subscribers, with broader access to Plus users rolling out over the coming weeks. Enterprise API pricing has been set at $15 per million input tokens and $60 per million output tokens — a premium over GPT-4o, but one that OpenAI argues is justified by the performance gains.</p>
 
<h2>Safety and Alignment at the Core</h2>
<p>OpenAI spent more than eight months on what it calls "alignment fine-tuning" for GPT-5, a process designed to make the model more honest, less prone to hallucination, and more resistant to adversarial manipulation. The company published a detailed safety report alongside the launch, revealing that GPT-5 refused harmful requests at twice the rate of its predecessor while producing fewer false refusals on legitimate queries.</p>
<p>Not everyone is satisfied. Several AI safety organizations have called for independent auditing before the model is deployed at scale, arguing that capabilities of this magnitude require external oversight. OpenAI has said it is open to third-party evaluation but has not committed to a timeline.</p>
 
<h2>What Comes Next</h2>
<p>With GPT-5 now public, attention is already turning to what lies beyond. OpenAI has hinted at a project internally referred to as "Orion," widely believed to be a prototype system exploring the boundaries of artificial general intelligence. Whether GPT-5 represents the last great leap before AGI or simply another step on a long road remains one of the most consequential open questions in technology today.</p>`,
