    types: ["main", "sidebar"],

    body: `<p>After years of debate, revision, and political negotiation, the European Union's Artificial Intelligence Act has officially entered full enforcement as of April 2026. The regulation, the first of its kind anywhere in the world, imposes strict requirements on companies developing or deploying AI systems within the EU — and its effects are already being felt across the global technology industry.</p>
 
<h2>A Risk-Based Framework</h2>
<p>The AI Act operates on a tiered risk model. Systems classified as presenting "unacceptable risk" — such as real-time biometric surveillance in public spaces and AI-powered social scoring — are outright banned. "High-risk" systems, including those used in hiring, credit scoring, medical diagnosis, and law enforcement, must now undergo mandatory conformity assessments, maintain detailed logs of their decision-making, and register in a new EU-wide database before deployment.</p>
<p>General-purpose AI models, including large language models with more than 100 billion parameters, face additional transparency obligations. Developers must publish technical documentation, conduct adversarial testing, and report serious incidents to national authorities within 72 hours of discovery.</p>
 
<h2>Big Tech Scrambles to Comply</h2>
<p>The enforcement deadline caught several companies in various states of readiness. Google, Microsoft, and Meta have all confirmed that dedicated compliance teams are now operational, but smaller AI startups have raised concerns about the cost and complexity of meeting the Act's requirements. The European AI Office, the newly created body responsible for overseeing compliance, has indicated it will prioritize enforcement actions against the highest-risk deployments first.</p>
<p><strong>Fines for non-compliance are severe:</strong> up to €35 million or 7% of global annual turnover for the most serious violations, and up to €15 million or 3% of turnover for lesser breaches. Several U.S.-based companies have already begun geofencing certain AI features to avoid triggering EU obligations.</p>
 
<h2>Global Ripple Effects</h2>
<p>Much like the GDPR before it, the AI Act is expected to exert influence well beyond Europe's borders. Countries including the United Kingdom, Japan, and Canada are observing the rollout closely, with regulatory proposals in each jurisdiction drawing heavily from the EU framework. Critics argue the regulation risks slowing innovation; supporters counter that it establishes the kind of trust that is essential for long-term AI adoption.</p>
<p>The coming months will be a critical test of whether the EU's ambitious regulatory vision can be enforced in practice — and whether it sets a global standard or simply shifts AI development to less regulated jurisdictions.</p>`,
