    types: ["main", "sidebar"],
    body: `<p>Bitcoin shattered the $150,000 price barrier on Sunday, reaching a new all-time high of $152,340 during early Asian trading hours before settling around $149,800 by mid-afternoon UTC. The milestone caps a remarkable six-month rally that has seen the world's largest cryptocurrency more than double in value, fueled by an unprecedented surge of institutional and sovereign capital entering the market.</p>
 
<h2>Institutions Lead the Charge</h2>
<p>Unlike previous bull cycles, which were largely driven by retail speculation, this rally has been characterized by large, systematic purchases from professional investors. Spot Bitcoin ETFs listed in the United States, which collectively launched in early 2024, now hold a combined total of over 1.2 million BTC — roughly 5.7% of the entire circulating supply. BlackRock's iShares Bitcoin Trust alone has seen net inflows exceeding $4 billion in the past 30 days.</p>
<p>Sovereign wealth funds have emerged as a new and significant force. Norway's Government Pension Fund Global, the Abu Dhabi Investment Authority, and Singapore's GIC are all reported to have allocated between 1% and 3% of assets to Bitcoin over the past 12 months, according to filings and sources familiar with the matter. <strong>"Digital gold is no longer a fringe thesis — it is mainstream portfolio construction,"</strong> said Fidelity Digital Assets president Tom Jessop in a statement following the price milestone.</p>
 
<h2>Supply Dynamics Amplify the Move</h2>
<p>The April 2024 halving, which cut Bitcoin's block reward from 3.125 BTC to 1.5625 BTC, has continued to compress the available supply entering the market. Miners are selling far less than they produce, and long-term holders — wallets that have not moved funds in over a year — now control a record 73% of all circulating Bitcoin. This illiquid supply environment means that even moderate increases in demand can produce outsized price moves.</p>
<p>On-chain analytics firm Glassnode estimates that at current demand levels, the so-called "liquid supply" of Bitcoin available on exchanges could be exhausted within 90 days if buying continues at the present pace.</p>
 
<h2>Caution Amid the Euphoria</h2>
<p>Not all market observers are celebrating. Several macro analysts have warned that Bitcoin's rapid ascent has pushed key valuation metrics — including the Market Value to Realized Value ratio — into territory historically associated with local tops. The derivatives market shows elevated funding rates and a high proportion of leveraged long positions, conditions that can lead to sharp corrections if momentum falters.</p>
<p>Regulators, too, are watching closely. The U.S. Treasury Department issued a statement reiterating that it continues to monitor digital asset markets for signs of systemic risk, while the Financial Stability Board has called for greater international coordination on crypto oversight. For now, however, the bulls appear firmly in control.</p>`,
