    summary:
      "Four astronauts have touched down near the lunar south pole in humanity's most ambitious Moon mission to date, marking the beginning of a permanent crewed presence on the Moon.",
    types: ["main", "sidebar"],
    body: `<p>NASA's Artemis IV mission achieved a historic milestone on Wednesday when its crew of four astronauts successfully landed near the lunar south pole at a site designated Shackleton Rim Alpha, less than two kilometers from the entrance to a permanently shadowed crater believed to contain significant water ice deposits. The landing marks the first time humans have set foot on the Moon since Apollo 17 in 1972 — and the first time any crew has visited the lunar south pole.</p>
 
<h2>A Mission Built on Years of Preparation</h2>
<p>Commander Keiko Yamamoto of JAXA, pilot Marcus Webb of NASA, mission specialists Dr. Aisha Osei of ESA, and geologist Dr. Rodrigo Castillo of the Canadian Space Agency touched down at 14:23 UTC aboard the SpaceX Human Landing System, Starship HLS Endurance. Mission controllers at Johnson Space Center erupted in applause as telemetry confirmed engine shutdown and a stable landing. "Shackleton Rim Alpha, Endurance is home," Yamamoto radioed to Earth moments after landing.</p>
<p>The Artemis IV mission builds on the earlier Artemis III crewed lunar orbit and the uncrewed Artemis II test of the Orion spacecraft's systems. Extensive robotic reconnaissance — including data from NASA's VIPER rover, which mapped the south pole region in 2024 — guided the selection of the landing site for its proximity to potential water ice, relatively flat terrain, and near-continuous sunlight for solar power generation.</p>
 
<h2>Scientific Objectives</h2>
<p>The crew is scheduled to spend seven days on the lunar surface, conducting geological surveys, collecting up to 100 kilograms of rock and regolith samples, and deploying a network of seismic sensors to study the Moon's interior structure. Most critically, they will drill into the floor of a permanently shadowed crater to extract samples from deposits that may have been undisturbed for billions of years.</p>
<p><strong>Water ice on the Moon could be transformative for future exploration.</strong> If present in sufficient quantities, it could be processed into drinking water, oxygen for life support, and hydrogen and oxygen propellant — potentially enabling a self-sustaining lunar base without the cost of resupplying from Earth. Initial VIPER data suggested concentrations of 5–8% water by mass in some shadowed areas, a figure that Artemis IV samples may help confirm or revise.</p>
 
<h2>Gateway and the Road to Permanence</h2>
<p>Artemis IV also marks the first use of the Lunar Gateway, the small space station orbiting the Moon that served as a staging point for the crew's descent. Gateway, assembled in 2025 by an international coalition including NASA, ESA, JAXA, and the Canadian Space Agency, is intended to become a permanent hub for lunar and deep-space exploration.</p>
<p>NASA Administrator Bill Nelson called the landing "the opening chapter of humanity's permanent return to the Moon," and confirmed that Artemis V — planned for 2028 — will deliver the first components of a surface habitat designed to support year-round crew rotations. China's CNSA, which landed its own taikonauts at a different south pole site in 2025, has proposed joint scientific data sharing, an offer NASA is reportedly reviewing.</p>`,
