    summary:
      "Marine biologists have mapped an enormous coral reef ecosystem 300 meters below the Atlantic's surface, teeming with species previously unknown to science.",
    types: ["main", "sidebar"],
    body: `<p>A team of marine scientists from the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, in collaboration with researchers from Portugal, Brazil, and France, has announced the discovery of one of the largest deep-water coral reef systems ever documented. Located approximately 300 meters below the surface of the central Atlantic Ocean, the reef complex spans an estimated 3,200 square kilometers — larger than the state of Rhode Island — and harbors a biodiversity that has stunned the scientific community.</p>
 
<h2>A World Hidden in the Deep</h2>
<p>The discovery was made during a 60-day research expedition aboard the RV Atlantis, using a combination of autonomous underwater vehicles and remotely operated submersibles equipped with high-resolution imaging systems. What began as a routine bathymetric mapping survey of a submerged seamount chain expanded dramatically when sonar readings revealed an unexpectedly complex three-dimensional structure extending across the seafloor.</p>
<p>Unlike shallow tropical reefs built primarily by stony corals dependent on sunlight and symbiotic algae, deep-water coral reefs are constructed by azooxanthellate corals — species that obtain energy from filtering organic particles out of the water column rather than from photosynthesis. The newly discovered system is dominated by Lophelia pertusa and a previously unknown species tentatively named Bathelia atlantica, which forms unusually large and intricately branched colonies up to four meters in height.</p>
 
<h2>Extraordinary Biodiversity</h2>
<p>Preliminary species counts from video analysis and physical samples collected during the expedition suggest the reef may harbor over 1,000 distinct species, including at least 12 that are entirely new to science. Among the new finds are three species of deep-sea fish, two species of basket star, and an undescribed species of giant isopod measuring nearly 40 centimeters in length.</p>
<p><strong>"Every dive produced something we had never seen before,"</strong> said expedition leader Dr. Sofia Marques of the University of Lisbon. "In 25 years of deep-sea research, I have never encountered a system this rich this far from any known biodiversity hotspot. It raises serious questions about how much of the deep Atlantic we still haven't explored."</p>
 
<h2>Conservation Concerns</h2>
<p>The reef's location puts it within international waters but also within the potential footprint of several planned deep-sea mining concessions. Environmental groups have called for immediate provisional protections while the scientific assessment is completed. The International Seabed Authority is expected to address the discovery at its next session in July.</p>
<p>The research team is preparing a detailed taxonomy report and has submitted a petition to UNESCO to have the area considered for designation as a Marine World Heritage site. A follow-up expedition is planned for late 2026 to deploy long-term monitoring equipment and collect samples for genomic analysis.</p>`,
