    summary:
      "The International Energy Agency has confirmed that solar photovoltaic power is now cheaper per kilowatt-hour than coal, gas, and nuclear energy in over 130 countries.",
    types: ["main", "sidebar"],
    body: `<p>The International Energy Agency has released its annual World Energy Outlook update, confirming what analysts have long projected: solar photovoltaic power has become the cheapest source of electricity generation in history. In more than 130 countries, new utility-scale solar projects now produce electricity at a lower levelized cost than any fossil fuel or nuclear alternative — a milestone that the IEA's executive director called "the most important energy price signal of the century."</p>
 
<h2>The Numbers Behind the Milestone</h2>
<p>The global average levelized cost of energy for new utility-scale solar now stands at $21 per megawatt-hour, compared to $65/MWh for new combined-cycle gas plants, $80/MWh for new coal plants, and $92/MWh for new nuclear. In the sunniest regions of the world — the Middle East, North Africa, and parts of South and Southeast Asia — solar costs have fallen as low as $12/MWh, a price that was considered impossible just a decade ago.</p>
<p>The cost reduction has been driven by a combination of factors: a 90% decline in the price of solar panels since 2010, improved manufacturing efficiency, larger project sizes, and increasingly competitive financing in emerging markets. China's dominance of the solar supply chain — it produces roughly 80% of the world's solar panels — has been a central driver of price compression, though this concentration has also raised supply chain security concerns in Western governments.</p>
 
<h2>Accelerating the Energy Transition</h2>
<p>The IEA report projects that solar will account for 40% of global electricity generation by 2030, up from 18% today. This acceleration is already reshaping energy investment flows: for the first time in 2025, clean energy attracted more than twice the capital of fossil fuels, with solar alone drawing $680 billion in new investment. The report also highlights a sharp increase in corporate power purchase agreements, with technology companies, manufacturers, and retail chains locking in long-term solar contracts to decarbonize their operations.</p>
<p><strong>Battery storage is increasingly complementing solar's growth.</strong> Utility-scale lithium-ion battery installations grew 80% in 2025, helping to address solar's intermittency challenge and extend the hours during which solar can serve as baseload power. In several markets, including California, Texas, and parts of Australia, solar-plus-storage systems are now outcompeting gas peaker plants on both cost and reliability.</p>
 
<h2>Challenges That Remain</h2>
<p>Despite the optimism, the IEA warns that the transition faces structural bottlenecks. Electricity grid infrastructure in many countries was designed for centralized fossil fuel generation and is not equipped to handle large volumes of distributed, variable solar output. Grid upgrades are estimated to require $21 trillion in investment globally by 2050. Permitting timelines for new transmission lines remain a particular constraint in the United States and Europe, where regulatory processes can delay projects by a decade or more.</p>
<p>Access also remains deeply unequal. Many low-income countries lack the financing mechanisms to attract solar investment, and the IEA estimates that 680 million people worldwide still have no access to electricity. The report calls for a tripling of concessional finance from multilateral development banks to ensure that the solar revolution reaches those who need it most.</p>`,
